rie kijima international comparative education skip to main content skip to main navigation stanford university school of education learning design and technology home ma programs suse stanford search this site about ice academics admissions our students faculty & research ice home home rie kijima rie kijima rie kijima year 2007 i returned to stanford in 2007 as a doctoral student in international and comparative education program after completing my master's degree in the same program in 2003 immediately following my graduation from stanford i landed with a position at the world bank during my four year stint i worked on lending operations in basic and tertiary sub sectors in morocco and tunisia and conducted research on the state of education in the middle east and north africa region i spent the final year in the vietnam country office to help prepare a higher education loan project and provide technical support in the areas of monitoring and evaluation my other work experience include interning with japan international cooperation agency tunis tunisia education development center newton ma and global link management tokyo japan to gain further experience working on education projects with the generous funding of the joint japan world bank graduate scholarship program i decided to pursue my doctoral degree at stanford to further train in research methods and to hone my knowledge in international development with a focus on education for my dissertation research i am employing quantitative and qualitative mixed methods to investigate the reasons why developing countries participate in cross national assessments more specifically i investigate the interplay between political forces and economic incentives associated with a country's decision to engage in national regional and international assessments in addition i employ quasi experimental methods in measuring the effect of policy interventions in developing countries i provide technical support in assessing the effect of longer instructional time in vietnam using its national assessment the rigorous training in research world class faculty and brilliant cohorts that i am surrounded by are true benefits of pursuing advanced degree at stanford i would not be where i am now without the training i received and the people i met at stanford i will be serving as a teaching assistant in quantitative methods for master's students in the ice ieapa program during the 2011 2012 academic year if you have any questions about the programs please feel free to get in touch with me our students ice ieapa ma papers testimonials careers in ice log in testimonials ice ieapa ma ice ph d ice ieapa alumni stanford university school of education 485 lasuen mall stanford ca 94305 3096 tel 650 723 2109 copyright 2012 stanford university all rights reserved site map contact suse admissions helpsu maps & directions suse it axess academic calendar stanford bulletin office of the registrar edmail stanfordwho stanfordyou login connect with us connect with us on facebook connect with us on twitter connect with us on youtube connect with us on flickr website by lyudmila christie suse it
